50|$|In 1831, Gee began {{restoration}} {{work on the}} Holy Trinity Doom, {{an early}} 15th-century painting of the Last Judgment. He received five guineas for his work.There is little contemporary information about Gee's work on the Doom, but conservation work begun in 1995 suggests he added outlines to the figures and repainted or recoloured some areas.There {{is no evidence that}} Gee significantly changed the painting's composition or symbolism.Gee also applied a coating of megilp to the painting. This <b>bituminous</b> <b>varnish</b> soon degraded and by 1873 the Doom was 'almost invisible'.|$|E

